title: MP Mini Select 3D ABS & Nylon Fan Shroud remix

description.text:
Remix of FDM_Guru's ABS fan shroud mod to fix some minor problems. Currently a work in progress.

Summary of changes:

  1. Replaced spring clip bracket with a stepped design, it was difficult to attach the clip with the original.

  2. Increased Screw hold depth to lower risk of stripping threads.

  3. Increased screw hold diameter (from 2mm to 2.6) to make screws easier to tighten and reduce thread wear.

  4. Moved screw holes away from wider side of shroud so they weren't coming as close to the inside wall as with the original design.

Notes:

It may be possible to print this without supports (I did so by mistake), but doing so could cause some issues with the spring clips on the side due. The spring clips on this remix have a more extreme overhang compared to the clips on the original.

I recommend a higher temperature filament (ABS, PETg, etc) over regular PLA for prints of this part.

title: The Ark of the Covenant - Diorama-KIT

description.text:
The Ark of the Covenant Diorama-kit

.

Information about the Ark of the Covenant:
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ark_of_the_Covenant

How to make:

  • Find a nice display box, or platform. (hobbystores online etc)
  • Find some wooden sticks. (most supermarkets should have them otherwise try some street food stands)
  • Find some plastic plant that can be used in the scene. (Dollar shops, decoration shops etc)
  • Resize the model parts to fit your display box/platform and size the model to fit the wooden sticks.
  • Print the models.
  • Sand the models.
  • Fit the model parts, the "Grail protection figures", "Wooden sticks", And "the Ark".
  • Base coat the models.
  • Put some simple cheap sculpting clay on your platform/display box.
  • Model the clay how you want the scene to be (ground, pools of water, stones, and roads etc.)
  • To give more stability to the figures while standing in the box you could press the figures into the clay (few millimeters should be ok) pull the figures out of the clay.
  • While the clay is drying.
  • Press your plastic plants into the scene.
  • To make the reed shore I cut pairs of hairs from a brush and painted them.
    • After the clay is dry, Paint the whole scene, drybrush weathering.
  • Fill the water pools with "still water" or transparent glue.
  • Let everything dry completely before putting on the top part of the display box.
    (otherwise the "still water" / glue will condensate on the inside of your display!)

description.text:
The bike magnetic smartphone support can carry your smartphone on the handlebars of your bicycle.

The model is FREE !. If you want, and if you appreciate the work, you can decide to donate a tip (or click here : https://www.paypal.me/CARALIG).

If you don't have a 3D printer, you can (once files downloaded), go to https://www.3dhubs.com/ and find somewone around you that will print it for you at the best price.

Once installed on the bike, and the magnets inserted in the magnets room, simply insert a metal plate (a tin can lid works well) under the support your smartphone and put your phone on the carrier. There you go !

Video : https://youtu.be/oFYW642AZW8

The support is divided into 5 files that are printable separately :
1-LowerHalfRing
2-UpperHalfRing
3-MagnetRoom
4-Adapter
5-lid

You can use the adapter in case your handlebar bike is not horizontal. There is 4 different positions to screw it depending the angle position you want to apply to the support

The diameter of the ring is 28mm

The support operation is a mixture of 3D Printing / recovery and recycling.
 
The additional parts needed for installation and operation of the support are listed here :

  • A Torx screwdriver 9 to open the old hard disk drive (http://urlz.fr/403X)
  • Pliers to get the magnets out of the hard drives
  • Allen key 6 side 4 mm to screwn the support on the handlebar (http://urlz.fr/4044)

Recovery / Recycling parts

  • 6 magnets salvaged from old 3 hard drives out of use (http://urlz.fr/403W). Your friends will probably have an old unused PC....Here is a video that explains the dismantling magnets of a hard disk (http://urlz.fr/4040).
    The important thing is to get neodymium magnets

  • 2 Screw length 20mm, with no male 5mm hexagonal screw and clamping nut 4 mm (http://urlz.fr/4043) for allen key 6 sides 4 mm (http://urlz.fr/40nU)

  • 2 hexagonals nuts with 5mm screws (http://urlz.fr/4045)

  • 1 caoutchouc band (or old inner tube) is used to fill the possible gap between the handlebar and the clamp

  • A Smartphone shell (example: http://urlz.fr/40nW)

  • 1 cover large tin can that have to be cutted to the dimensions of your smartphone

Make sure at the end, that your smartphone is very well sticked with the magnet on the support. Do enough tests to be confident with it. You also have the possibility to secure it with elastics and or a thin nylon thread that you can pass into holes of the support. You are fully responsible of what you are doing and i'm declining all responsabilities in any case if your smartphone falls from the bike and is damaged.

title: BLTOUCH Holder for Folger Tech FT-5

description.text:
I took the BLTOUCH holder for the FT 2020 i3 and mated it with the cooling block spacer to make a holder for the FT-5 since there didn't seem to be one for the stock hot end. I couldn't use the one for the 2020 i3 because the cooling block doesn't extend out the left side on the FT-5.
There are two versions. The #2 version is 2mm lower than #3. I raised the heat break tube above the top of the cooling block to get it closer to the output of the extruder. This makes it easier to feed in new filament and also reduces the chances of a jam above the cooling block. That meant I needed version #3. You might, depending on your situation, need to add spacers to lower the BLTOUCH to get the up and down positions correct.
My offsets work out to -27 X and 27 Y. Z FOR ME is 1.05 but it depends on how you assembled your hotend.

The only thing different that I might suggest is to MIRROR it in your slicer so that the BLTOUCH is on the other side and away from the cable chain. I'll do that eventually too, when I have a chance.

comments.text: There are a few ways you can do it.  You can search google for abs acetone bath.  Personally, I used to put a splash of acetone in a glass bowl and let it heat up on the build plate of the printer (I know other people will advise against this, so do so at your own caution), now I have an electric stove, so I just let it heat on there.  Once it warms up, you just put the part in the air above the acetone for a few seconds at a time until you're happy with it. It will get soft and smudge where you touch it, and over exposure will cause it to "melt" and warp.  There are cold acetone vapor methods, but it will take like a half hour or something vs seconds.  I haven't personally attempted a cold vapor bath.

Center cores (all printable without support if you rotate them 180 degrees):

  • 82mm: 2-reel base core
  • extension core

Cog lid:

Future work:

title: e3d v5/v6 printrite extruder assembly (FINAL VERSION)

description.text:
this is the final version of my E3D/J-Head mod for the Printrite diy printer.

after countless prototyping and alterations this is the most self contained practical version Ive came up with which is both simple, versatile, easily printed, easily assembled, easy to maintain and easy to adjust.

simply designing parts to fit onto the existing printrite carriage proved inefficient and less than ideal so this design also includes a redesigned carriage replacement which has proven more sturdy, stable and less prone to cracks than the piece of cack plastic Collido originally used.

the original carriage bearings can be used but these were undersized even on the original carriage so I used 4x LM8UU 8mm bearings which have reduced noise and vibration across the Z-axis and give the carriage a much smoother glide, the redsigned carriage can still accommodate the original Printrite style extruder or even dual extruders of the same type (the mounting holes for the extruder bar are still available beneath were the e3d mount stands)

the Extruder mount is designed to "snap-on" and "snap-off" the carriage and is secured with 2x 2x10mm (easy access)screws/bolts on the sides making any maintenance or extruder swapping/tip replacing a simpler job as the whole mount comes away from the carriage(with extruder and coolers still attached) which gives excellent access to the extruder without the need for mass dismantling .

the mount can accommodate either the E3d V5 or E3d "all-metal" V6 extruders, its also compatible with the Chinese clones of both these models (often referred to as "J-head " extruders), there is a cable guide built into the design which will assist with keeping everything tidy and reduce any stress on the heater and thermistor points caused by the constant carriage movement during use.

the Tip cooler is bolted directly to the extruder mount with 2x 20mm M2 bolts through the top of the mount, this gives the tip cooler a limited degree of adjustment to account for fine tuning (roughly 7-8mm up & down movement which allows you to precisely aim were you want your cooling to strike the surface), this has proved more than enough adjustment for any of the various j-head/e3d extruders ive tested so far.

Ive included two versions of the extruder cooler, one is for the much slimmer e3d V6 all-metal extruder while the other fits the thicker V5, (the v5 version fits the clones also)

Im sure there's a couple of other features Im forgetting about but you'll probably come across them yourselves if you use this design anyway so heyho.

As said I intend this to be my final version of this particular mod as I cant see any need for further adaptions given that Ive found it works exactly as intended and required.

If anyone has any suggestion for further improvements and modification then please by all means...............

..............keep em to ya feckin selves, this last bugger made me bleed (see carriage front in above pictures) so Im not touching it again except with a hammer if it ever even attempts to injure me again.

Have fun, Print happy.

ps. Sorry I forgot to take photo's of the freshly printed parts as I usually do for reference, I forgot so all the photos show the parts post acetone vapour treated....... just incase anyone was wondering if I used a 0.0000001mm tip so the print layers didnt show

for anyone interested in doing this mod may I suggest you opt for the e3d v6 All-metal extruder (or one of the more decent China clones available at a fraction of the price).

after trying various J-head/e3d types and variants I can unanimously state that the e3d v6 all-metal is by far the best extruder of this type and its design features offers up a great deal less faffing about with dodgy ptfe throats and blocked nozzles while giving excellent stable temps at the hotend and the option of using filaments that require greater temp levels than PLA or ABS require (which on a standard extruder head would see the PTFE tube breaking down almost immediately and blocking the tip)

This e3d V6 clone version off ebay in particular has proven to be very capable and even matched up against the genuine print for print while costing less than a quarter of what you'd pay for the genuine version......

title: ArChery Cam Print All at Once - no assembly needed

description.text:
Update: Instead of 3D printed riser I decided to use the PVC pipe, like you can see on one of the pictures.
To lighten and stabilize the cam I've put all the parts together. Print with support as necessary, no assembly needed afterwards. Due to lack of metal screws the design is lighter and more stable.
Adjust fill % and wall thickness when printing to get the desired strength and weight.
I printed with 25%, 0.8mm wall.
My 20x20 print area allowed for only 0.85 scale of original size.
This is work in progress. I might add axles to get rid of bearings and support the cams on wider pivot base for stability.

Summary

Modified brackets to accommodate DN25 PVC pressure pipe. Outside diameter of the pipe before flattening: 33.5mm.

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1755555

Or just plain PVC pipe bent to shape as in many YouTube videos:
https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=how+to+make+PVC+bow

Alignment of the cams

After assembly some one or both of the cams might turn out to be not parallel to each other and not running smoothly on the cord. If that is your case just heat one side of the affected arm of the bow and twist it until parallel. It will be well visible on the "string". Let is set by cooling down. Voila!
Tension the strings and cut the ends with hot soldering iron and tie when everything aligns well.
For the "bearings" of the cams I just 3D printed small barrel like washers fitting sides of the cam or use real bearings.

description.text:
We donate any tips provided to the project -> Unesco - help for children.

There are 99GoodReasons to light a candle - it's a statement!
This thing 99GoodReasons (Visible) includes the frame for the Candle Holder (2 files) that you mix and match with a variety of sqaures in order to personalize your tealight. You find a selection below - more to come. There is an optional shade avialable.

It's a perfect and very personal gift for your friends and family! Have fun!

Use the plates included in this "Thing" or follow the links below to find more:

  • new: New York: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1776635
  • Halloween: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1767878
  • more to come

There is also a customizable gift box available:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1787739

Your own design:
-> Find attached a blank square as STL or Sketchup File

For safety reason we strongly recommend the use of electric tealights (LED).

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

I recommend to print using ABS. The two candle holder are easy to be print. You should not require to rotate them to print (however, both parts have clearly a "flat" side that will be on the print platform.

All squares should be correctly aligned. For best print results, ensure that the larger surface is aligned to the print platform.
The squares currently have no tolerance included. You may consider to print it with a scale at 99.75% for the "Hidden Version" - so the squares do not bend, when inserted in the holder.

For your personal designs you need to ensure to correct direction of a written text (mirroring).
The extent of light shining through the surface (the thickness of the wall/the square) may highly depend on your printer, the slicing software and print material. You may choose a thinner version of the squares, but increasing thickness may not work, as it not suits the holder.

Simplicity of a square

Versatile Light and Lamps have always been a personal passion. My earlier designs of lights and lamps did lack simplicity. Therefore the design of "99GoodReasons" focus on the very basic geometry of a square. A simple square enables the use of customized design:

  • using availble designed squares on different themes
  • using the customizer feature to personalize
  • or with very basic modelling techniques.

Currently there are two designs:

  • a (white) box where the text/image is hidden, until lit by a candle
  • the second design is more open, where the square are visible (and may cast shadows on a wall.
  • We also finalizing an electric version

Of course, all squares can be use for all variants.

description.text:
Belted Extruder V.3 for 2.85mm

This is the 2.85mm version of my Belted Extruder v.3 for 1.75.

Please note that I've published a Belted Extruder v4 - 2.85mm / 3mm.

Brackets etc.
Everything for my Belted Extruders, including Mounting brackets can be found in the my Collection: Belted Extruders by Dintid.

Notes: I removed the 3mm from the name as it is naitively too tight to use 3mm filaments. (all E3D 3mm is really 2.85mm).
You can enlarge the center conduit using a small metal-drill by hand if you want to use it for 3mm filaments.

  • You do not have to open idler to load filament, which makes it very easy to change filament!
  • Silent running due to belt operation
  • Higher accuracy and longelevity due to aluminium gears instead of printed gears.
  • Build in mount points on 3 sides. Compatible with standard Nema 17 brackets - 31mm mount hole distance from center to center.
  • I have printed a lot of Ninja-Flex SemiFlex and it works super nicely

Details

  • I use a 60-GT2 aluminium pulley to avoid inaccuracies and avoid wear and tear of printed gear.
  • I am using a 16-GT2 Pulley for my small gear, which gives a ratio of 1:3.75
  • If you use a 20-GT2 Pulley for small gear you get ratio 1:3
  • Belt needed 172-180
  • A Nema 17 motor - I use a standard Nema 17 with a bit over 4kg holding torque.
  • Belt is tightened by sliding motor away.
  • Strongly advice you to buy Hobbed Bolt from E3D
  • Using the Ultimaker 2 Bowden Couplers - can be found for cheap on Aliexpress and similar - buy extras as they do wear down eventually.
  • With 32 microstepping and normal 1.8 degree Nema, the steps are about 1100mm/s filament, so ultra high definition and high torque

BOM

  • 60GT-2 Pulley
  • 16GT-2 or 20GT-2 Pulley
  • E3D Hobbed Bolt - Hobb-Goblin-8mm-Shaft
  • A belt with length between: 172-GT2 to 180-GT2.
  • 2x Ultimaker 2 Bowden Couplers
  • Your Bowden tube must be OD 6.4mm to fit the above Couplers. I am using E3D bowden tube - NOTE that E3D's "3mm standard" is in fact 2.85mm and you can not use real 3mm bought from other places.
  • 2x 20mm steel springs. 1mm thick
  • 2x m3 50mm (or longer) Partially Threaded Socket Head Cap screws
  • 3x 608 bearings. 8x22x7 - Type doesn't matter.
  • Various m3 nuts, screws and spacers

I have created some brackets for usage with my Belted Extruders fit for most surfaces, including 2020 profiles.

Brackets for my Extruders

I've made a Collection named Belted Extruders by Dintid where all my items related to my Belted Extruders is going to be added.

Please let me know if you need a special bracket.

My Crossbot design

Notes:

Print files as oriented.

  • I printed using 0.4mm nozzle
  • Just use normal PLA - I Used PrimaSelect PLA Black
  • 3 Perimeters/Borders
  • 3 Top and Bottom layers
  • Use a strong Infil like Triangles in Cura 2.3
  • All necessary supports are build in
  • Use 50% infill or higher.
  • Do not make weak finger-release parts
  • You CAN print with 0.25mm layerheight but it results in visibly oblong holes. It does work though
Remove supports colored red here.

description.header: GT2 Belts to use and not
description.text: 172-2GT to 180-2GT are good. Anything above is too long. Make sure there is no clogging of the center hole. Start by putting a piece of filament through the main body before assembling. If you can't get the UM2 bowden coupler into the hole, you use a 7,5mm metal drill and enlarge the outer rim by hand. You can use 16-GT2 for 1:3.75 gear ration and 20-GT2 for 1:3 gear ratio. How the inner workings of the Bowden Coupling is constructed.

Chinese paper lanterns, spray glue, dowel, WS2811 RGB LEDs, polyfil, arduino nano, HC-05 bluetooth module

Colorful video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=18ojSVLnwEU

Lightning video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OvdQdgDKFlE

Case for solderable breadboard that holds my circuit:
https://www.tinkercad.com/things/d0vNP6qnxQN-super-habbi/edit? (STL is attached)

Circuit

The circuit is super simple. There's an arduino nano, a 5v/3v level shifter, and an HC-05 bluetooth module, all soldered into a solderable breadboard.

That contraption talks to my android phone via Software Serial. There's a photo of the circuit attached. I'm happy to draw it out if you leave a comment and ask for it, or feel free to ask questions.

The arduino nano uses a 5v/3.3v level shifter like this one to drop to 3.3v for the HC-05 bluetooth module, since that module isn't rated for 5V logic (it's okay to give it 5V power):
http://www.ebay.com/itm/3x-Bi-Directional-Logic-Level-Shifter-Converter-4-CH-3-3V-5V-For-Arduino-I2C-IIC-/131521259438

The tape on the various components is hiding the arduino and bluetooth status LEDs.

Software

This was my first attempt at messing with Android apps, so I imported Mantas Palaima's excellent bluetooth arduino app as a starting point. I've committed the changes I've made so far, and will have more to come:

https://github.com/bobiam/AndroidSmoothBluetooth

The arduino code to control the lights themselves is here:
https://github.com/bobiam/dasblinkencloud

Oh, you're one of today's lucky 10,000!

Update!
Improved.stl is a new one. 3mm thick and recessed
for those who do not want to widen the bores (not for the guards)
for the cylinder-screws and want to use counter-sink-screws instead.

======================================================
Although there are many real 3d fan-guards and some screwless ones
I did not find a combination of both, or at least one I liked.
So I made one.
It is not just an optical thing, the aerodynamics is better with this design
which leaves some space between mesh and fan.
With the flat designs some fans audibly stall for lack of incoming air.
Due to the pins it surely is an awkward job printing it,
the look of it is worth the effort, though.
In my experience it is best to be printed with the pins down
and the mesh up using a raft and supports.
Low temperature and speed for best results.
As with all my designs there is no or only little give implemented!
Just some little sanding or cleaning with a knife at the pins is enough to fit perfectly.
It is designed for pabst fans with 3,2-3,4mm bores.
For bigger bores I made good experience with some melting glue at the pins.
Once the glue has hardened the guard even can be de- and reasembled.

description.text:
Some simple 3d printed parts I designed for my FX-61 flying wing.

  1. A motor mount reinforcing part. I printed this in ABS and glued it inside the rather fragile looking stock motor mount.

  2. A ring which fits on the spinner to prevent the folding prop from flying forwards and hitting the wing or motor surround during motor start-up. The ring is designed to fit this spinner: http://www.hobbyking.com/hobbyking/store/__17622__Folding_Prop_Spinner_38mm_4_0mm_shaft.html
    Print this in nylon.
    In addition, a piece of aluminium sheet prevents the blades crossing, which can result in them failing to open out when the motor starts.

  3. An aerodynamic guard to protect the elevon servos and horns on landings, printed in PLA. I glued this onto the underside of the wing using hot melt glue.

  4. A simple bracket for mounting the push button switch for the Pixhawk flight computer so that the button protrudes through a small hole in the cover.

Hello
This is a very early version of my Y6 hexacopter based on the multicopter frame inspired by Benedikt Haak's dream catcher quadcopter frame.

Frame

I have used the thingyverse customizer to generate a standard Micro Tricopter frame.
Then I have used 123D design and 3D builder to double this frame by copy/paste
I have also added some reinforcement to make it stiffer.

This is not a double deck frame.

Upper motor mounts will be on the "front frame" and lower motor mounts will be installed in the "back frame".

There are 2 versions of the frame at the moment; V2 is the standard one.
V3 version is almost the same, except that there is a lower plate so that you can fit an front cam on it for FPV

Upper Motor Mounts

I use the motor mounts of the original design for the upper motors (just shortened a little).
I plan to use slide the motor mount into the frame then rotate it to keep it in place
The 2 "shoulders" on the side of the part at the bottom should maintain the motor mount in place once rotated.

(I will add real photos and make some adjustments as soon as I have printed the first model)

Lower Motor Mounts

I have heavily modified the motor mounts of the original design for the lower motor mounts (added to some "shoulders").
I plan to use slide the motor mount into the frame then rotate it to keep it in place using the same as the one use for the upper motor mounts
The extra "shoulders" on the side of the parts should maintain the motor mount in place once rotated.

Please bear in mind that this motor mount will seat upside down.

Legs

I am not happy yet with the design of the legs but it is mandatory to put some.
Otherwise you will land on the bottom propellers

Extra Hardware needed

I had planned to use the electronic from the Cheerson CX 33 to get the controller board and the motors.I would need to invert polarity on the motors as the Cheerson is using a gearbox and I plan to go direct drive.

However, dur to a recent change in Cheerson CX 33 communication protocol, I cannot use a real transmitter anymore (Devo 7e with deviation Tx)..

So I will probably go for the Eachine 32bits F3 Brushed FCB Based On SP RACING F3 EVO (or something similar):
http://www.banggood.com/Eachine-32bits-F3-Brushed-Flight-Control-Board-Based-On-SP-RACING-F3-EVO-For-Micro-FPV-Frame-p-1076530.html?utmid=1006

And some 8520 brushed shaolin motors; If I refer to screenshot from cleanflight. i probably need 4 CW motors and 2 CCW motors (to be confirmed)
